		Subject:&nbsp;<b>RE: Ranged slot...</b></font>
		
		<a href="MB_Editmsg.asp?FID=67&FN=Paladin&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=2035482&TN=Ranged+slot%2E%2E%2E&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=2043073&PL=4&amp;action=REPLY"><img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/btn_reply.gif" border="0" align="right" alt="Reply to message"></a>
		<br>
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/Icons/icon1.gif" border="0" align="ABSCENTER" width="15" height="15">
		<font size="2" face="Verdana">
		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 10/7/2003 6:13:50 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=67&FN=Paladin&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=2035482&TN=Ranged+slot%2E%2E%2E&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=2043073&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">Aye, the Z-axis and things getting in the way is a pain.</P><P>In the lower levels, with a smaller mana pool, the stun spells are much more costly at those levels, so using a bow can save valuable mana, 15 mana for cease at level 60+ is barely even worth scoffing at, so the value of a Bow seems to be a low to mid level thing.</P><P>Now of course when pulling, there are several things that come to mind, one is you generally are trying to only get 1 critter to follow you home, so in most cases you don't want to pull with a stun spell that has a duration, and leaves the critter standing there, especially in open places or where there are wondering mobs. You pull and you want the critter to follow you. So you won't be using just any stun, and thus you have a spell slot dedicated to a spell used just for pulling. I myself when grouped have a line up of spells up that includes 4 heals, root and 2 stuns(Akilae and Akera), which leaves one spell slot. In this space I put up what utility spell I might need depending in the situation. Pulling with stuns requires that I use this space for a insta-duration stun (becuase the others will leave the critter standing there stunned) using a bow frees this space up for other spells, like keeping my haste spell up in case it wears off, cure spells, etc that often come in handy or are needed. I keep the other 2 stuns up for their relative low mana cost, they can stun most critters, and I find it generally takes 2 stuns (min)to be effective at chain stuning to interupt casters, especially ones that Gate or Complete heal. However in most cases I prefer not to use them to pull since as stated before, it leaves the critter standing where it is until the stun duration fades (Cease is ussually the best to use for pulling, lowest mana cost and the duration is instant so the critter follows right away)</P><P>Now when you are splitting critters using Pacify and lull spells. Then you should be aware that using stuns and other spells to pull generates an agro radius, whereas using an arrow doesn't. For example, using lull on the Shadowmen in East commons, you pacify or harmony then and use an arrow to pull, and you get just the critter you hit with an arrow, however, use a stun spell to pull and you get every single one of them. Also when pulling skelly camps in Kunark, you will discover that using an arrow to pull the skellys brings you one skelly, no need to pacify the camp, however use a spell and you get the whole lot. (at least at the level that you get experience off these) Arrows generate less of an agro field arround them when used, whereas the spell agro radius is very noticable. Now to be honest I've obbserved that as I've gained in levels this agro generation from using spells or arrows becomes less and less of an issue, and is practically unnoticable at 65.</P><P>Using stun to pull to pregenerate agro is useful when you are tanking, but when you are pulling for someone else (probably because your Pacifying the critters and pulling singles) then you really don't want to generate any more agro then you have to, so a bow really comes in handy there. (I use it while pulling in the basement jail in PoJ fer example, where I can pacify the critters and pull singles)</P><P>So in comclusion I would say that at low and mid levels, get a bow. However in the 50 to 60+ game, you can safely go without, unless you simply enjoy using them. <br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
